# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: pandas-dataframe
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] CSV is not limited to a particular character encoding but should be and is commonly used with UTF-8, particularly because it does not provide a way to indicate the character encoding.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The CSV format predates personal computers by more than a decade.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The IBM Fortran (level H extended) compiler under OS/360 supported list-directed ("free-form") input/output, with commas between values, in 1972.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] List-directed input/output was defined in FORTRAN 77, approved in 1978.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] List-directed input used commas or spaces for delimiters, so unquoted character strings could not contain commas or spaces.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The term "comma-separated value" and the "CSV" abbreviation were in use by 1983.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The manual for the Osborne Executive computer, which bundled the SuperCalc spreadsheet, documents the CSV quoting convention that allows strings to contain embedded commas.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Comma-separated value lists are easier to type (for example into punched cards) than fixed-column-aligned data, and they were less prone to producing incorrect results if a value was punched one column off from its intended location.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Comma separated files are used for the interchange of database information between machines of two different architectures.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The plain-text character of CSV files largely avoids incompatibilities such as byte-order and word size.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The files are largely human-readable, so it is easier to deal with them in the absence of perfect documentation or communication.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The main standardization initiative—transforming "*de facto* fuzzy definition" into a more precise and *de jure* one—was in 2005, with RFC 4180, defining CSV as a MIME Content Type.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Later, in 2013, some of RFC 4180's deficiencies were tackled by a W3C recommendation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] In 2014 IETF published RFC 7111 describing the application of URI fragments to CSV documents.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] RFC 7111 specifies how row, column, and cell ranges can be selected from a CSV document using position indexes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] In 2015 W3C, in an attempt to enhance CSV with formal semantics, publicized the first *drafts of recommendations* for CSV metadata standards, which began as *recommendations* in December of the same year.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] CSV can be informally described as plain text data consisting of one record per line, where each line has the same sequence of fields separated by a comma.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The format is more formally described in the 2005 technical standard RFC 4180 which codifies the CSV format and defines the MIME type `text/csv` for the handling of text-based fields.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] This example illustrates that a CSV cannot be parsed by naïvely splitting the data by line terminators into lines, and then each line by commas.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] In 2011, Open Knowledge Foundation (OKF) and various partners created a data protocols working group, which later evolved into the Frictionless Data initiative.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] One of the main formats they released was the Tabular Data Package.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Tabular Data package was heavily based on CSV, using it as the main data transport format and adding basic type and schema metadata.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] (CSV lacks any type information to distinguish the string `1` from the number 1.) The Frictionless Data Initiative has also provided a standard CSV Dialect Description Format for describing different dialects of CSV, for example specifying the field separator or quoting rules.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] In 2013, the W3C "CSV on the Web" working group began to specify technologies providing higher interoperability for web applications using CSV or similar formats.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] The working group completed its work in February 2016 and is officially closed in March 2016 with the release of a set of documents and W3C recommendations for modeling "Tabular Data", and enhancing CSV with metadata and semantics.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] While the well-formedness of CSV data can readily be checked, testing validity and canonical form is less well developed, relative to more precise data formats, such as XML and SQL, which offer richer types and rules-based validation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] CSV is commonly used for data exchange and is widely supported by data-oriented applications.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] It is often used to move tabular data between programs that natively operate on incompatible data – often in formats that are proprietary or undocumented.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] A common scenario is moving data from a database to a spreadsheet which, in general, use completely different formats.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Most database systems can export as CSV and most spreadsheet programs can import CSV-formatted data, leveraging CSV as an intermediate format.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Every major ecommerce platform provides support for exporting data as a CSV file.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Common data science tools such as Pandas include the option to export data to CSV for long-term storage.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Benefits of CSV for data storage include the simplicity of CSV makes parsing and creating CSV files easy to implement and fast compared to other data formats, human readability making editing or fixing data simpler, and high compressibility leading to smaller data files.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Alternatively, CSV does not support more complex data relations and makes no distinction between null and empty values, and in applications where these features are needed other formats are preferred.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] More than 200 local, regional, and national data portals, such as those of the UK government and the European Commission, use CSV files with standardized data catalogs.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Some applications use CSV as a data interchange format to enhance its interoperability, exporting and importing CSV.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] CSV is supported by almost all spreadsheets and database management systems.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Spreadsheets including Apple Numbers, LibreOffice Calc, and Apache OpenOffice Calc. support reading CSV files.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Microsoft Excel also supports a dialect of CSV with restrictions in comparison to other spreadsheet software (e.g., as of 2019 Excel still cannot export CSV files in the commonly used UTF-8 character encoding, and separator is not enforced to be the comma).
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] LibreOffice Calc CSV importer is actually a more generic delimited text importer, supporting multiple separators at the same time as well as field trimming.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Various relational databases support saving query results to a CSV file.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] PostgreSQL provides the `COPY` command, which allows for both saving and loading data to and from a file.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] `COPY (SELECT * FROM articles) TO '/home/wikipedia/file.csv' (FORMAT csv)` saves the content of a table `articles` to a file called `/home/wikipedia/file.csv`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Some relational databases, when using standard SQL, offer *foreign-data wrapper* (FDW).
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] For example, PostgreSQL offers the `CREATE FOREIGN TABLE` and `CREATE EXTENSION file_fdw` commands to configure any variant of CSV.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Databases like Apache Hive offer the option to express CSV or .csv.gz as an internal table format.
[src:pandas-dataframe/comma-separated-values] Programs that work with CSV may have limits on the maximum number of rows CSV files can have.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A **data model** is an abstract model that organizes elements of data and standardizes how they relate to one another and to the properties of real-world entities.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For instance, a data model may specify that the data element representing a car be composed of a number of other elements which, in turn, represent the color and size of the car and define its owner.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The corresponding professional activity is called generally *data modeling* or, more specifically, *database design*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data models are typically specified by a data expert, data specialist, data scientist, data librarian, or a data scholar.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data modeling language and notation are often represented in graphical form as diagrams.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model can sometimes be referred to as a data structure, especially in the context of programming languages.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data models are often complemented by function models, especially in the context of enterprise models.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model explicitly determines the *structure of data*; conversely, **structured data** is data organized according to an explicit data model or data structure.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Structured data is in contrast to *unstructured data* and *semi-structured data*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The term ***data model*** can refer to two distinct but closely related concepts.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Sometimes it refers to an abstract formalization of the objects and relationships found in a particular application domain: for example the customers, products, and orders found in a manufacturing organization.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] At other times it refers to the set of concepts used in defining such formalizations: for example concepts such as entities, attributes, relations, or tables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] So the "data model" of a banking application may be defined using the entity–relationship "data model".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This article uses the term in both senses.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Managing large quantities of structured and unstructured data is a primary function of information systems.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data models describe the structure, manipulation, and integrity aspects of the data stored in data management systems such as relational databases.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] They may also describe data with a looser structure, such as word processing documents, email messages, pictures, digital audio, and video: XDM, for example, provides a data model for XML documents.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The main aim of data models is to support the development of information systems by providing the definition and format of data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] According to West and Fowler (1999) "if this is done consistently across systems then compatibility of data can be achieved.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] If the same data structures are used to store and access data then different applications can share data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The results of this are indicated above.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] However, systems and interfaces often cost more than they should, to build, operate, and maintain.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] They may also constrain the business rather than support it.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A major cause is that the quality of the data models implemented in systems and interfaces is poor".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The reason for these problems is a lack of standards that will ensure that data models will both meet business needs and be consistent.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model explicitly determines the structure of data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Typical applications of data models include database models, design of information systems, and enabling exchange of data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Logical data model: describes the semantics, as represented by a particular data manipulation technology.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This consists of descriptions of tables and columns, object oriented classes, and XML tags, among other things.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Physical data model: describes the physical means by which data are stored.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This is concerned with partitions, CPUs, tablespaces, and the like.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The significance of this approach, according to ANSI, is that it allows the three perspectives to be relatively independent of each other.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Storage technology can change without affecting either the logical or the conceptual model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The table/column structure can change without (necessarily) affecting the conceptual model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In each case, of course, the structures must remain consistent with the other model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The table/column structure may be different from a direct translation of the entity classes and attributes, but it must ultimately carry out the objectives of the conceptual entity class structure.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Early phases of many software development projects emphasize the design of a conceptual data model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such a design can be detailed into a logical data model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In later stages, this model may be translated into physical data model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] However, it is also possible to implement a conceptual model directly.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] One of the earliest pioneering works in modeling information systems was done by Young and Kent (1958), who argued for "a precise and abstract way of specifying the informational and time characteristics of a data processing problem".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] They wanted to create "a notation that should enable the analyst to organize the problem around any piece of hardware".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Their work was the first effort to create an abstract specification and invariant basis for designing different alternative implementations using different hardware components.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The next step in IS modeling was taken by CODASYL, an IT industry consortium formed in 1959, who essentially aimed at the same thing as Young and Kent: the development of "a proper structure for machine-independent problem definition language, at the system level of data processing".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This led to the development of a specific IS information algebra.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In the 1960s data modeling gained more significance with the initiation of the management information system (MIS) concept.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] According to Leondes (2002), "during that time, the information system provided the data and information for management purposes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The first generation database system, called Integrated Data Store (IDS), was designed by Charles Bachman at General Electric.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Two famous database models, the network data model and the hierarchical data model, were proposed during this period of time".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Codd worked out his theories of data arrangement, and proposed the relational model for database management based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In the 1970s entity–relationship modeling emerged as a new type of conceptual data modeling, originally formalized in 1976 by Peter Chen.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Entity–relationship models were being used in the first stage of information system design during the requirements analysis to describe information needs or the type of information that is to be stored in a database.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This technique can describe any ontology, i.e., an overview and classification of concepts and their relationships, for a certain area of interest.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Nijssen developed "Natural Language Information Analysis Method" (NIAM) method, and developed this in the 1980s in cooperation with Terry Halpin into Object–Role Modeling (ORM).
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] However, it was Terry Halpin's 1989 PhD thesis that created the formal foundation on which Object–Role Modeling is based.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Bill Kent, in his 1978 book *Data and Reality,* compared a data model to a map of a territory, emphasizing that in the real world, "highways are not painted red, rivers don't have county lines running down the middle, and you can't see contour lines on a mountain".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In contrast to other researchers who tried to create models that were mathematically clean and elegant, Kent emphasized the essential messiness of the real world, and the task of the data modeler to create order out of chaos without excessively distorting the truth.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Harrington (2000), "the development of the object-oriented paradigm brought about a fundamental change in the way we look at data and the procedures that operate on data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Traditionally, data and procedures have been stored separately: the data and their relationship in a database, the procedures in an application program.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] During the early 1990s, three Dutch mathematicians Guido Bakema, Harm van der Lek, and JanPieter Zwart, continued the development on the work of G.M.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] They focused more on the communication part of the semantics.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In 1997 they formalized the method Fully Communication Oriented Information Modeling FCO-IM.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A database model is a specification describing how a database is structured and used.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Several such models have been suggested.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This may not strictly qualify as a data model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The flat (or table) model consists of a single, two-dimensional array of data elements, where all members of a given column are assumed to be similar values, and all members of a row are assumed to be related to one another.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The hierarchical model is similar to the network model except that links in the hierarchical model form a tree structure, while the network model allows arbitrary graph.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] , organizes data using two fundamental constructs, called records and sets.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Records (or nodes) contain fields (i.e. attributes), and sets (or edges) define one-to-many, many-to-many and many-to-one relationships between records: one owner, many members.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The network data model is an abstraction of the design concept used in the implementation of databases.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Network models emphasise interconnectedness, making them ideal for applications where relationships are crucial, like social networks or recommendation systems.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This structure allows for efficient querying of relationships without expensive joins.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] is a database model based on first-order predicate logic.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Its core idea is to describe a database as a collection of predicates over a finite set of predicate variables, describing constraints on the possible values and combinations of values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The power of the relational data model lies in its mathematical foundations and a simple user-level paradigm.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A method of data modeling that has been defined as "attribute free", and "fact-based".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The result is a verifiably correct system, from which other common artifacts, such as ERD, UML, and semantic models may be derived.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Associations between data objects are described during the database design procedure, such that normalization is an inevitable result of the process.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The simplest style of data warehouse schema.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The star schema consists of a few "fact tables" (possibly only one, justifying the name) referencing any number of "dimension tables".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data structure diagram (DSD) is a diagram and data model used to describe conceptual data models by providing graphical notations which document entities and their relationships, and the constraints that bind them.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The basic graphic elements of DSDs are boxes, representing entities, and arrows, representing relationships.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data structure diagrams are most useful for documenting complex data entities.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data structure diagrams are an extension of the entity–relationship model (ER model).
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In DSDs, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as boxes composed of attributes which specify the constraints that bind entities together.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] DSDs differ from the ER model in that the ER model focuses on the relationships between different entities, whereas DSDs focus on the relationships of the elements within an entity and enable users to fully see the links and relationships between each entity.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with the notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The choices are between arrow heads, inverted arrow heads (crow's feet), or numerical representation of the cardinality.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] An entity–relationship model (ERM), sometimes referred to as an entity–relationship diagram (ERD), could be used to represent an abstract conceptual data model (or semantic data model or physical data model) used in software engineering to represent structured data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There are several notations used for ERMs.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Like DSD's, attributes are specified inside the entity boxes rather than outside of them, while relationships are drawn as lines, with the relationship constraints as descriptions on the line.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The E-R model, while robust, can become visually cumbersome when representing entities with several attributes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There are several styles for representing data structure diagrams, with a notable difference in the manner of defining cardinality.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model in Geographic information systems is a mathematical construct for representing geographic objects or surfaces as data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Generic data models are generalizations of conventional data models.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] They define standardized general relation types, together with the kinds of things that may be related by such a relation type.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Generic data models are developed as an approach to solving some shortcomings of conventional data models.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For example, different modelers usually produce different conventional data models of the same domain.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This can lead to difficulty in bringing the models of different people together and is an obstacle for data exchange and data integration.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Invariably, however, this difference is attributable to different levels of abstraction in the models and differences in the kinds of facts that can be instantiated (the semantic expression capabilities of the models).
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The modelers need to communicate and agree on certain elements that are to be rendered more concretely, in order to make the differences less significant.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A semantic data model in software engineering is a technique to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A semantic data model is an abstraction that defines how the stored symbols relate to the real world.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A semantic data model is sometimes called a conceptual data model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The logical data structure of a database management system (DBMS), whether hierarchical, network, or relational, cannot totally satisfy the requirements for a conceptual definition of data because it is limited in scope and biased toward the implementation strategy employed by the DBMS.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Therefore, the need to define data from a conceptual view has led to the development of semantic data modeling techniques.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] That is, techniques to define the meaning of data within the context of its interrelationships with other data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The real world, in terms of resources, ideas, events, etc., are symbolically defined within physical data stores.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Thus, the model must be a true representation of the real world.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data architecture is the design of data for use in defining the target state and the subsequent planning needed to hit the target state.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It is usually one of several architecture domains that form the pillars of an enterprise architecture or solution architecture.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data architecture describes the data structures used by a business and/or its applications.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There are descriptions of data in storage and data in motion; descriptions of data stores, data groups, and data items; and mappings of those data artifacts to data qualities, applications, locations, etc.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Essential to realizing the target state, Data architecture describes how data is processed, stored, and utilized in a given system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It provides criteria for data processing operations that make it possible to design data flows and also control the flow of data in the system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data modeling in software engineering is the process of creating a data model by applying formal data model descriptions using data modeling techniques.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data modeling is a technique for defining business requirements for a database.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It is sometimes called *database modeling* because a data model is eventually implemented in a database.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The figure illustrates the way data models are developed and used today.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A conceptual data model is developed based on the data requirements for the application that is being developed, perhaps in the context of an activity model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The data model will normally consist of entity types, attributes, relationships, integrity rules, and the definitions of those objects.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This is then used as the start point for interface or database design.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Another kind of data model describes how to organize data using a database management system or other data management technology.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It describes, for example, relational tables and columns or object-oriented classes and attributes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such a data model is sometimes referred to as the *physical data model*, but in the original ANSI three schema architecture, it is called "logical".
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In that architecture, the physical model describes the storage media (cylinders, tracks, and tablespaces).
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Ideally, this model is derived from the more conceptual data model described above.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It may differ, however, to account for constraints like processing capacity and usage patterns.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A different approach is to use adaptive systems such as artificial neural networks that can autonomously create implicit models of data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data structure is a way of storing data in a computer so that it can be used efficiently.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It is an organization of mathematical and logical concepts of data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Often a carefully chosen data structure will allow the most efficient algorithm to be used.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The choice of the data structure often begins from the choice of an abstract data type.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model describes the structure of the data within a given domain and, by implication, the underlying structure of that domain itself.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This means that a data model in fact specifies a dedicated *grammar* for a dedicated artificial language for that domain.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model represents classes of entities (kinds of things) about which a company wishes to hold information, the attributes of that information, and relationships among those entities and (often implicit) relationships among those attributes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The model describes the organization of the data to some extent irrespective of how data might be represented in a computer system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The entities represented by a data model can be the tangible entities, but models that include such concrete entity classes tend to change over time.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Robust data models often identify abstractions of such entities.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For example, a data model might include an entity class called "Person", representing all the people who interact with an organization.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such an abstract entity class is typically more appropriate than ones called "Vendor" or "Employee", which identify specific roles played by those people.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model *instance*, i.e. applying a data model *theory* to create a practical data model *instance* for some particular application.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For example, in the relational model, the structural part is based on a modified concept of the mathematical relation; the integrity part is expressed in first-order logic and the manipulation part is expressed using the relational algebra, tuple calculus and domain calculus.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data model instance is created by applying a data model theory.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This is typically done to solve some business enterprise requirement.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Business requirements are normally captured by a semantic logical data model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This is transformed into a physical data model instance from which is generated a physical database.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For example, a data modeler may use a data modeling tool to create an entity–relationship model of the corporate data repository of some business enterprise.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] This model is transformed into a relational model, which in turn generates a relational database.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Patterns are common data modeling structures that occur in many data models.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data-flow diagram (DFD) is a graphical representation of the "flow" of data through an information system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It differs from the flowchart as it shows the *data* flow instead of the *control* flow of the program.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] A data-flow diagram can also be used for the visualization of data processing (structured design).
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Data-flow diagrams were invented by Larry Constantine, the original developer of structured design, based on Martin and Estrin's "data-flow graph" model of computation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It is common practice to draw a context-level data-flow diagram first which shows the interaction between the system and outside entities.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The **DFD** is designed to show how a system is divided into smaller portions and to highlight the flow of data between those parts.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] An Information model is not a type of data model, but more or less an alternative model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Within the field of software engineering, both a data model and an information model can be abstract, formal representations of entity types that include their properties, relationships and the operations that can be performed on them.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The entity types in the model may be kinds of real-world objects, such as devices in a network, or they may themselves be abstract, such as for the entities used in a billing system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Typically, they are used to model a constrained domain that can be described by a closed set of entity types, properties, relationships and operations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] According to Lee (1999) an information model is a representation of concepts, relationships, constraints, rules, and operations to specify data semantics for a chosen domain of discourse.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It can provide sharable, stable, and organized structure of information requirements for the domain context.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] More in general the term *information model* is used for models of individual things, such as facilities, buildings, process plants, etc.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In those cases the concept is specialised to Facility Information Model, Building Information Model, Plant Information Model, etc.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such an information model is an integration of a model of the facility with the data and documents about the facility.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] An information model provides formalism to the description of a problem domain without constraining how that description is mapped to an actual implementation in software.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There may be many mappings of the information model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such mappings are called data models, irrespective of whether they are object models (e.g. using UML), entity–relationship models or XML schemas.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] An object model in computer science is a collection of objects or classes through which a program can examine and manipulate some specific parts of its world.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In other words, the object-oriented interface to some service or system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such an interface is said to be the *object model of* the represented service or system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For example, the Document Object Model (DOM) is a collection of objects that represent a page in a web browser, used by script programs to examine and dynamically change the page.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There is a Microsoft Excel object model for controlling Microsoft Excel from another program, and the ASCOM Telescope Driver is an object model for controlling an astronomical telescope.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] In computing the term *object model* has a distinct second meaning of the general properties of objects in a specific computer programming language, technology, notation or methodology that uses them.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] For example, the *Java object model*, the *COM object model*, or *the object model of OMT*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Such object models are usually defined using concepts such as class, message, inheritance, polymorphism, and encapsulation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] There is an extensive literature on formalized object models as a subset of the formal semantics of programming languages.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Object–Role Modeling (ORM) is a method for conceptual modeling, and can be used as a tool for information and rules analysis.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] Object–Role Modeling is a fact-oriented method for performing systems analysis at the conceptual level.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The quality of a database application depends critically on its design.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] To help ensure correctness, clarity, adaptability and productivity, information systems are best specified first at the conceptual level, using concepts and language that people can readily understand.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The conceptual design may include data, process and behavioral perspectives, and the actual DBMS used to implement the design might be based on one of many logical data models (relational, hierarchic, network, object-oriented, etc.).
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] The Unified Modeling Language (UML) is a standardized general-purpose modeling language in the field of software engineering.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] It is a graphical language for visualizing, specifying, constructing, and documenting the artifacts of a software-intensive system.
[src:pandas-dataframe/data-model] UML offers a mix of functional models, data models, and database models.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] pandas provides various methods for combining and comparing `Series` or `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `concat()` function concatenates an arbitrary amount of `Series` or `DataFrame` objects along an axis while performing optional set logic (union or intersection) of the indexes on the other axes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Like `numpy.concatenate`, `concat()` takes a list or dict of homogeneously-typed objects and concatenates them.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `concat()` makes a full copy of the data, and iteratively reusing `concat()` can create unnecessary copies.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Collect all `DataFrame` or `Series` objects in a list before using `concat()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] When concatenating `DataFrame` with named axes, pandas will attempt to preserve these index/column names whenever possible.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] In the case where all inputs share a common name, this name will be assigned to the result.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] When the input names do not all agree, the result will be unnamed.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The same is true for `MultiIndex`, but the logic is applied separately on a level-by-level basis.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `join` keyword specifies how to handle axis values that don’t exist in the first `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `join='outer'` takes the union of all axis values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `join='inner'` takes the intersection of the axis values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] To perform an effective “left” join using the *exact index* from the original `DataFrame`, result can be reindexed.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] For `DataFrame` objects which don’t have a meaningful index, the `ignore_index` ignores overlapping indexes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] You can concatenate a mix of `Series` and `DataFrame` objects.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `Series` will be transformed to `DataFrame` with the column name as the name of the `Series`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Unnamed `Series` will be numbered consecutively.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `ignore_index=True` will drop all name references.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `keys` argument adds another axis level to the resulting index or column (creating a `MultiIndex`) associate specific keys with each original `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `keys` argument can override the column names when creating a new `DataFrame` based on existing `Series`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `levels` argument allows specifying resulting levels associated with the `keys`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] If you have a `Series` that you want to append as a single row to a `DataFrame`, you can convert the row into a `DataFrame` and use `concat()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge()` performs join operations similar to relational databases like SQL.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Users who are familiar with SQL but new to pandas can reference a comparison with SQL.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge()` implements common SQL style joining operations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] When joining columns on columns, potentially a many-to-many join, any indexes on the passed `DataFrame` objects **will be discarded**.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] For a **many-to-many** join, if a key combination appears more than once in both tables, the `DataFrame` will have the **Cartesian product** of the associated data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `how` argument to `merge()` specifies which keys are included in the resulting table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] If a key combination **does not appear** in either the left or right tables, the values in the joined table will be `NA`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] You can merge `Series` and a `DataFrame` with a `MultiIndex` if the names of the `MultiIndex` correspond to the columns from the `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Merging on duplicate keys significantly increase the dimensions of the result and can cause a memory overflow.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `validate` argument checks whether the uniqueness of merge keys.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Key uniqueness is checked before merge operations and can protect against memory overflows and unexpected key duplication.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] If the user is aware of the duplicates in the right `DataFrame` but wants to ensure there are no duplicates in the left `DataFrame`, one can use the `validate='one_to_many'` argument instead, which will not raise an exception.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge()` accepts the argument `indicator`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] A string argument to `indicator` will use the value as the name for the indicator column.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `DataFrame.join()` combines the columns of multiple, potentially differently-indexed `DataFrame` into a single result `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `DataFrame.join()` takes an optional `on` argument which may be a column or multiple column names that the passed `DataFrame` is to be aligned.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The default for `DataFrame.join` is to perform a left join which uses only the keys found in the calling `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Other join types can be specified with `how`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] You can join a `DataFrame` with a `Index` to a `DataFrame` with a `MultiIndex` on a level.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `name` of the `Index` will match the level name of the `MultiIndex`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `MultiIndex` of the input argument must be completely used in the join and is a subset of the indices in the left argument.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Strings passed as the `on`, `left_on`, and `right_on` parameters may refer to either column names or index level names.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] This enables merging `DataFrame` instances on a combination of index levels and columns without resetting indexes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] When `DataFrame` are joined on a string that matches an index level in both arguments, the index level is preserved as an index level in the resulting `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] When `DataFrame` are joined using only some of the levels of a `MultiIndex`, the extra levels will be dropped from the resulting join.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] To preserve those levels, use `DataFrame.reset_index()` on those level names to move those levels to columns prior to the join.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] A list or tuple of `DataFrame` can also be passed to `join()` to join them together on their indexes.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `DataFrame.combine_first()` update missing values from one `DataFrame` with the non-missing values in another `DataFrame` in the corresponding location.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge_ordered()` combines ordered data such as numeric or time series data with optional filling of missing data with `fill_method`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge_asof()` is similar to an ordered left-join except that matches are on the nearest key rather than equal keys.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] For each row in the `left` `DataFrame`, the last row in the `right` `DataFrame` is selected where the `on` key is less than the left’s key.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Both `DataFrame` must be sorted by the key.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Optionally `merge_asof()` can perform a group-wise merge by matching the `by` key in addition to the nearest match on the `on` key.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge_asof()` within `2ms` between the quote time and the trade time.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] `merge_asof()` within `10ms` between the quote time and the trade time and exclude exact matches on time.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Note that though we exclude the exact matches (of the quotes), prior quotes **do** propagate to that point in time.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The `Series.compare()` and `DataFrame.compare()` methods allow you to compare two `DataFrame` or `Series`, respectively, and summarize their differences.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] By default, if two corresponding values are equal, they will be shown as `NaN`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Furthermore, if all values in an entire row / column are equal, that row / column will be omitted from the result.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] The remaining differences will be aligned on columns.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Keep all original rows and columns with `keep_shape=True`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/merging] Keep all the original values even if they are equal.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In statistics, **missing data**, or **missing values**, occur when no data value is stored for the variable in an observation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missing data are a common occurrence and can have a significant effect on the conclusions that can be drawn from the data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missing data can occur because of nonresponse: no information is provided for one or more items or for a whole unit ("subject").
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Some items are more likely to generate a nonresponse than others: for example items about private subjects such as income.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Attrition is a type of missingness that can occur in longitudinal studies—for instance studying development where a measurement is repeated after a certain period of time.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missingness occurs when participants drop out before the test ends and one or more measurements are missing.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Data often are missing in research in economics, sociology, and political science because governments or private entities choose not to, or fail to, report critical statistics, or because the information is not available.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Sometimes missing values are caused by the researcher—for example, when data collection is done improperly or mistakes are made in data entry.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] These forms of missingness take different types, with different impacts on the validity of conclusions from research: Missing completely at random, missing at random, and missing not at random.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missing data can be handled similarly as censored data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Understanding the reasons why data are missing is important for handling the remaining data correctly.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] If values are missing completely at random, the data sample is likely still representative of the population.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] But if the values are missing systematically, analysis may be biased.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Because of these problems, methodologists routinely advise researchers to design studies to minimize the occurrence of missing values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Graphical models can be used to describe the missing data mechanism in detail.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Values in a data set are **missing completely at random (MCAR)** if the events that lead to any particular data-item being missing are independent both of observable variables and of unobservable parameters of interest, and occur entirely at random.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] When data are MCAR, the analysis performed on the data is unbiased; however, data are rarely MCAR.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In the case of MCAR, the missingness of data is unrelated to any study variable: thus, the participants with completely observed data are in effect a random sample of all the participants assigned a particular intervention.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] With MCAR, the random assignment of treatments is assumed to be preserved, but that is usually an unrealistically strong assumption in practice.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Samuelson and Spirer (1992) discussed how missing and/or distorted data about demographics, law enforcement, and health could be indicators of patterns of human rights violations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] They gave several fairly well documented examples.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missing data can also arise in subtle ways that are not well accounted for in classical theory.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] An increasingly encountered problem arises in which data may not be MAR but missing values exhibit an association or structure, either explicitly or implicitly.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Such missingness has been described as ‘structured missingness’.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Structured missingness commonly arises when combining information from multiple studies, each of which may vary in its design and measurement set and therefore only contain a subset of variables from the union of measurement modalities.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In these situations, missing values may relate to the various sampling methodologies used to collect the data or reflect characteristics of the wider population of interest, and so may impart useful information.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For instance, in a health context, structured missingness has been observed as a consequence of linking clinical, genomic and imaging data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] The presence of structured missingness may be a hindrance to make effective use of data at scale, including through both classical statistical and current machine learning methods.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For example, there might be bias inherent in the reasons why some data might be missing in patterns, which might have implications in predictive fairness for machine learning models.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Furthermore, established methods for dealing with missing data, such as imputation, do not usually take into account the structure of the missing data and so development of new formulations is needed to deal with structured missingness appropriately or effectively.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Finally, characterising structured missingness within the classical framework of MCAR, MAR, and MNAR is a work in progress.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missing data can also be a deliberate part of study design.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Missing data reduces the representativeness of the sample and can therefore distort inferences about the population.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] One systematic review addressing the prevention and handling of missing data for patient-centered outcomes research identified 10 standards as necessary for the prevention and handling of missing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] These include standards for study design, study conduct, analysis, and reporting.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In some practical application, the experimenters can control the level of missingness, and prevent missing values before gathering the data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For example, in computer questionnaires, it is often not possible to skip a question.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] A question has to be answered, otherwise one cannot continue to the next.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] So missing values due to the participant are eliminated by this type of questionnaire, though this method may not be permitted by an ethics board overseeing the research.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In survey research, it is common to make multiple efforts to contact each individual in the sample, often sending letters to attempt to persuade those who have decided not to participate to change their minds.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In situations where missing values are likely to occur, the researcher is often advised on planning to use methods of data analysis methods that are robust to missingness.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] An analysis is robust when we are confident that mild to moderate violations of the technique's key assumptions will produce little or no bias, or distortion in the conclusions drawn about the population.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Some data analysis techniques are not robust to missingness, and require to "fill in", or impute the missing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Rubin (1987) argued that repeating imputation even a few times (five or less) enormously improves the quality of estimation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For many practical purposes, two or three imputations capture most of the relative efficiency that could be captured with a larger number of imputations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] However, a too-small number of imputations can lead to a substantial loss of statistical power, and some scholars now recommend 20 to 100 or more.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Any multiply-imputed data analysis must be repeated for each of the imputed data sets and, in some cases, the relevant statistics must be combined in a relatively complicated way.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Multiple imputation is not conducted in specific disciplines, as there is a lack of training or misconceptions about them.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Methods such as listwise deletion have been used to impute data but it has been found to introduce additional bias.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] There is a beginner guide that provides a step-by-step instruction how to impute data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] The expectation-maximization algorithm is an approach in which values of the statistics which would be computed if a complete dataset were available are estimated (imputed), taking into account the pattern of missing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In this approach, values for individual missing data-items are not usually imputed.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In the mathematical field of numerical analysis, interpolation is a method of constructing new data points within the range of a discrete set of known data points.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In the comparison of two paired samples with missing data, a test statistic that uses all available data without the need for imputation is the partially overlapping samples t-test.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Partial identification methods may also be used.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Model based techniques, often using graphs, offer additional tools for testing missing data types (MCAR, MAR, MNAR) and for estimating parameters under missing data conditions.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For any three variables *X,Y*, and *Z* where *Z* is fully observed and *X* and *Y* partially observed, the data should satisfy: $X\perp \!\!\!\perp R_{y}|(R_{x},Z)$ .
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In words, the observed portion of *X* should be independent on the missingness status of *Y,* conditional on every value of *Z*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Failure to satisfy this condition indicates that the problem belongs to the MNAR category.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] When data falls into MNAR category, techniques are available for consistently estimating parameters when certain conditions hold in the model.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For example, if *Y* explains the reason for missingness in *X,* and *Y* itself has missing values, the joint probability distribution of *X* and *Y* can still be estimated if the missingness of *Y* is random.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] where $R_{x}=0$ and $R_{y}=0$ denote the observed portions of their respective variables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Different model structures may yield different estimands and different procedures of estimation whenever consistent estimation is possible.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] The preceding estimand calls for first estimating $P(X|Y)$ from complete data and multiplying it by $P(Y)$ estimated from cases in which *Y* is observed regardless of the status of *X*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Moreover, in order to obtain a consistent estimate it is crucial that the first term be $P(X|Y)$ as opposed to $P(Y|X)$ .
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In many cases model based techniques permit the model structure to undergo refutation tests.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Any model which implies the independence between a partially observed variable *X* and the missingness indicator of another variable *Y* (i.e. $R_{y}$ ), conditional on $R_{x}$ can be submitted to the following refutation test: $X\perp \!\!\!\perp R_{y}|R_{x}=0$ .
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] Finally, the estimands that emerge from these techniques are derived in closed form and do not require iterative procedures such as Expectation Maximization that are susceptible to local optima.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] A special class of problems appears when the probability of the missingness depends on time.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] For example, in the trauma databases the probability to lose data about the trauma outcome depends on the day after trauma.
[src:pandas-dataframe/missing-data] In these cases various non-stationary Markov chain models are applied.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] The development of Pandas introduced into Python many comparable features of working with DataFrames that were established in the R programming language.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] The library is built upon another library, NumPy.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Developer Wes McKinney started working on Pandas in 2008 while at AQR Capital Management out of the need for a high performance, flexible tool to perform quantitative analysis on financial data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Before leaving AQR, he was able to convince management to allow him to open source the library in 2009.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Another AQR employee, Chang She, joined the effort in 2012 as the second major contributor to the library.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] In 2015, Pandas signed on as a fiscally sponsored project of NumFOCUS, a 501(c)(3) nonprofit charity in the United States.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Pandas is built around data structures called *Series* and *DataFrames*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Data for these collections can be imported from various file formats such as comma-separated values, JSON, Parquet, SQL database tables or queries, and Microsoft Excel.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] A *Series* is a one-dimensional array-like object that stores a sequence of values together with an associated set of labels, called an index.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] It is built on top of NumPy's array and affords many similar functionalities, but instead of using implicit integer positions, a Series allows explicit index labels of many data types.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] A Series can be created from Python lists, dictionaries, or NumPy arrays.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] If no index is provided, pandas automatically assigns a default integer index ranging from 0 to n-1, where n is the number of items in the Series.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Series can be used arithmetically, as in the statement `series_3 = series_1 + series_2`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] This will align data points with corresponding index values in `series_1` and `series_2` (similar to a join in relational algebra), then add them together to produce new values in `series_3`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] A Series has various attributes, such as `name` (Series name), `dtype` (data type of values), `shape` (number of rows), `values`, and `index`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] They can be used in many of the same operations as NumPy arrays, with additional methods for reindexing, label-based selection, and handling missing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] A *DataFrame* is a two-dimensional, tabular data structure with labeled rows and columns.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Each column is stored internally as a Series and may hold a different data type (numeric, string, boolean, etc.).
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] To retrieve a DataFrame column as a Series, use either 1) the index (dict-like notation) or 2) the name of column if the name is a valid Python identifier (attribute-like access).
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] DataFrames support operations such as column assignment, row and column deletion, label-based indexing with `loc`, position-based indexing with `iloc`, reshaping, grouping, and joining.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Merge operations implement a subset of relational algebra and allow one-to-one, many-to-one, and many-to-many joins.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] pandas' syntax for mapping index values to relevant data is the same syntax Python uses to map dictionary keys to values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] For example, if `s` is a Series, `s['a']` will return the data point at index `a`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Unlike dictionary keys, index values are not guaranteed to be unique.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] If a Series uses the index value `a` for multiple data points, then `s['a']` will instead return a new Series containing all matching values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] A DataFrame's column names are stored and implemented identically to an index.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] As such, a DataFrame can be thought of as having two indices: one column-based and one row-based.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Because column names are stored as an index, these are not required to be unique.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] If `data` is a Series, then `data['a']` returns all values with the index value of `a`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] However, if `data` is a DataFrame, then `data['a']` returns all values in the column(s) named `a`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] To avoid this ambiguity, Pandas supports the syntax `data.loc['a']` as an alternative way to filter using the index.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Pandas also supports the syntax `data.iloc[n]`, which always takes an integer *n* and returns the *nth* value, counting from 0.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] This allows a user to act as though the index is an array-like sequence of integers, regardless of how it is actually defined.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] pandas also supports hierarchical indices with multiple values per data point through the "MultiIndex" class.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] MultiIndex objects allow a single DataFrame to represent multiple dimensions, similar to a pivot table in Microsoft Excel, where each level can optionally carry its own unique name.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] In practice, data with more than 2 dimensions is often represented using DataFrames with hierarchical indices, instead of the higher-dimension *Panel* and *Panel4D* data structures.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] pandas supports a variety of indexing and subsetting techniques, allowing data to be selected by label, index, or Boolean conditions.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] For example, `df[df['col1'] > 5]` will return all rows in the DataFrame `df` for which the value of the column `col1` exceeds 5.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] The library also implements grouping operations based on the split-apply-combine approach, enabling users to aggregate, transform, or restructure data according to column values or functions applied to index labels.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] For example, `df['col1'].groupby(df['col2'])` groups the data in 'col1' by their values in 'col2', while `df.groupby(lambda i: i % 2)` groups all data in the whole DataFrame by whether their index is even.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] The library also provides extensive tools for transforming, filtering and summarizing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Users may apply arbitrary functions to Series and DataFrames, and because the library is built on top of Numpy, most NumPy functions can be applied directly to pandas objects as well.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] The library also includes built-in operations for arithmetic operations, string processing, and descriptive statistics such as mean, median, and standard deviation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] These built-in functions are designed to handle missing data, usually represented by the floating-point value NaN.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] In addition, pandas includes tools for reorganizing data into different structural formats, with methods that can reshape tabular data between "wide" and "long" formats and pivot values based on column labels. pandas also implements a flexible set of relational operations for combining datasets.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] For instance, `merge()` links row in DataFrames based on one or more shared keys or indices, supporting one-to-one, one-to-many, and many-to-many relationships in a manner analogous to join operations in relational databases like SQL.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] DataFrames can also be concatenated or stacked together along an axis through the `concat()` method, and overlapping data can be further spliced together using `combine_first()` to fill in missing values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Furthermore, the library includes specialized support for working with time-series data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Features include the ability to interpolate values and filter using a range of timestamps, such as `data['1/1/2023':'2/2/2023']` , which will return all dates between January 1 and February 2.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Missing values in time-series data are represented by a dedicated NaT (Not a Timestamp) object, instead of the NaN value it uses elsewhere.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Pandas has been criticized for its inefficiency.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] The entire dataset must be loaded in RAM, and the library does not optimize query plans or support parallel computing across multiple cores.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Wes McKinney, the creator of Pandas, has recommended Apache Arrow as an alternative to address these performance concerns and other limitations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Otherwise, he says, "my rule of thumb for pandas is that you should have 5 to 10 times as much RAM as the size of your dataset".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Sort foods by calories (descending order):df.sort_values("calories", ascending=False) Note: Any missing values are automatically sorted to the end of the Series.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Group items by category and calculate average macros:df.groupby("category")[["carb_g", "fat_g", "protein_g"]].mean() This returns a GroupBy object that is analogous to a collection of DataFrames.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Find the highest-calorie food per category:df.loc[df.groupby("category")["protein_g"].idxmax()] `idxmax()` returns the index value of the maximum value.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] `idxmin()` performs an analogous function with the minimum value.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Handle missing data:df.loc[2, "fiber_g"] = None # Simulate a missing value df["fiber_g"].fillna(df["fiber_g"].mean()) This replaces the `None` value with `NaN`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Alternatively, we can also drop rows containing missing values by calling `df.dropna()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] To merge datasets with different key column names, use the parameters `left_on` and `right_on` instead.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pandas-software] Categorize food by calories:df["calorie_level"] = pd.cut( df["calories"], bins=[0,100,200,300], labels=["Low", "Medium", "High"] ) This splits numeric data into separate "bins" or intervals, thereby allowing continuous measurements to be analyzed as discrete categories.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A **pivot table** is a table of values which are aggregations of groups of individual values from a more extensive table (such as from a database, spreadsheet, or business intelligence program) within one or more discrete categories.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] The aggregations or summaries of the groups of the individual terms might include sums, averages, counts, or other statistics.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A pivot table is the outcome of the statistical processing of tabularized raw data and can be used for decision-making.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Although *pivot table* is a generic term, Microsoft held a trademark on the term in the United States from 1994 to 2020.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In their book *Pivot Table Data Crunching*, Bill Jelen and Mike Alexander refer to Pito Salas as the "father of pivot tables".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] While working on a concept for a new program that would eventually become Lotus Improv, Salas noted that spreadsheets have patterns of data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A tool that could help the user recognize these patterns would help to build advanced data models quickly.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] With Improv, users could define and store sets of categories, then change views by dragging category names with the mouse.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This core functionality would provide the model for pivot tables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Lotus Development released Improv in 1991 on the NeXT platform.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A few months after the release of Improv, Brio Technology published a standalone Macintosh implementation, called DataPivot (with technology eventually patented in 1999).
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Borland purchased the DataPivot technology in 1992 and implemented it in their own spreadsheet application, Quattro Pro.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In 1993 the Microsoft Windows version of Improv appeared.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Early in 1994 Microsoft Excel 5 brought a new functionality called a "PivotTable" to market.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In 2007 Oracle Corporation made `PIVOT` and `UNPIVOT` operators available in Oracle Database 11g.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] While tables such as these can contain many data items, it can be difficult to get summarized information from them.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A pivot table can help quickly summarize the data and highlight the desired information.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] The usage of a pivot table is extremely broad and depends on the situation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A pivot table usually consists of *row*, *column* and *data* (or *fact*) fields.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In this case, the column is *ship date*, the row is *region* and the data we would like to see is (sum of) *units*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] These fields allow several kinds of aggregations, including: sum, average, standard deviation, count, etc.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In this case, the total number of units shipped is displayed here using a *sum* aggregation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Using the example above, the software will find all distinct values for *Region*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In this case, they are: *North*, *South*, *East*, *West*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Furthermore, it will find all distinct values for *Ship date*.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Based on the aggregation type, *sum*, it will summarize the fact, the quantities of *Unit*, and display them in a multidimensional chart.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In the example above, the first datum is 66.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This number was obtained by finding all records where both *Region* was *East* and *Ship Date* was *2005-01-31*, and adding the *Units* of that collection of records (*i.e.*, cells E2 to E7) together to get a final result.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Pivot tables are not created automatically.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] For example, in Microsoft Excel one must first select all of the data in the original table and then go to the Insert tab and select "Pivot Table" (or "Pivot Chart").
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] The user then has the option of either inserting the pivot table into an existing sheet or creating a new sheet to house the pivot table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] A pivot table field list is provided to the user which lists all the column headers present in the data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] For instance, if a table represents sales data of a company, it might include Date of sale, Sales person, Item sold, Color of item, Units sold, Per unit price, and Total price.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This makes the data more readily accessible.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] The fields that would be created will be visible on the right hand side of the worksheet.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] By default, the pivot table layout design will appear below this list.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Pivot Table fields are the building blocks of pivot tables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Some uses of pivot tables are related to the analysis of questionnaires with optional responses but some implementations of pivot tables do not allow these use cases.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] For example the implementation in LibreOffice Calc since 2012 is not able to process empty cells.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Report filter is used to apply a filter to an entire table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] For example, if the "Color of Item" field is dragged to this area, then the table constructed will have a report filter inserted above the table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This report filter will have drop-down options (Black, Red, and White in the example above).
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] When an option is chosen from this drop-down list ("Black" in this example), then the table that would be visible will contain only the data from those rows that have the "Color of Item= Black".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Column labels are used to apply a filter to one or more columns that have to be shown in the pivot table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] For instance if the "Salesperson" field is dragged to this area, then the table constructed will have values from the column "Sales Person", *i.e.*, one will have a number of columns equal to the number of "Salesperson".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] There will also be one added column of Total.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In the example above, this instruction will create five columns in the table — one for each salesperson, and Grand Total.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] There will be a filter above the data — column labels — from which one can select or deselect a particular salesperson for the pivot table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This table will not have any numerical values as no numerical field is selected but when it is selected, the values will automatically get updated in the column of "Grand total".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Row labels are used to apply a filter to one or more rows that have to be shown in the pivot table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] For instance, if the "Salesperson" field is dragged on this area then the other output table constructed will have values from the column "Salesperson", *i.e.*, one will have a number of rows equal to the number of "Sales Person".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] There will also be one added row of "Grand Total".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] In the example above, this instruction will create five rows in the table — one for each salesperson, and Grand Total.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] There will be a filter above the data — row labels — from which one can select or deselect a particular salesperson for the Pivot table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This table will not have any numerical values, as no numerical field is selected, but when it is selected, the values will automatically get updated in the Row of "Grand Total".
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] This usually takes a field that has numerical values that can be used for different types of calculations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] However, using text values would also not be wrong; instead of Sum, it will give a count.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] So, in the example above, if the "Units sold" field is dragged to this area along with the row label of "Salesperson", then the instruction will add a new column, "Sum of units sold", which will have values against each salesperson.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Pivot tables or pivot functionality are an integral part of many spreadsheet applications and some database software, as well as being found in other data visualization tools and business intelligence packages.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Several JavaScript UI frameworks and web application libraries provide components for embedding pivot tables in web applications.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Programming languages and libraries suited to work with tabular data contain functions that allow the creation and manipulation of pivot tables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Excel pivot tables include the feature to directly query an online analytical processing (OLAP) server for retrieving data instead of getting the data from an Excel spreadsheet.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] On this configuration, a pivot table is a simple client of an OLAP server.
[src:pandas-dataframe/pivot-table] Excel's PivotTable not only allows for connecting to Microsoft's Analysis Service, but to any XML for Analysis (XMLA) OLAP standard-compliant server.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A **table** is an arrangement of information or data, typically in rows and columns, or possibly in a more complex structure.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tables are widely used in communication, research, and data analysis.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tables appear in print media, handwritten notes, computer software, architectural ornamentation, traffic signs, and many other places.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The precise conventions and terminology for describing tables vary depending on the context.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Further, tables differ significantly in variety, structure, flexibility, notation, representation and use.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Information or data conveyed in table form is said to be in **tabular** format (adjective).
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] In books and technical articles, tables are typically presented apart from the main text in numbered and captioned floating blocks.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A **table cell** is one grouping within a chart table used for storing information or data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Cells are grouped horizontally (rows of cells) and vertically (columns of cells).
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Each cell contains information relating to the combination of the row and column headings it is collinear with.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A table consists of an ordered arrangement of **rows** and **columns**.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] This is a simplified description of the most basic kind of table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The elements of a table may be grouped, segmented, or arranged in many different ways, and even nested recursively.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Additionally, a table may include metadata, annotations, a header, a footer or other ancillary features.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The following illustrates a simple table with four columns and nine rows.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The first row is not counted, because it is only used to display the column names.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The concept of **dimension** is also a part of basic terminology.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Any "simple" table can be represented as a "multi-dimensional" table by normalizing the data values into ordered hierarchies.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A common example of such a table is a multiplication table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] In multi-dimensional tables, each cell in the body of the table (and the value of that cell) relates to the values at the beginnings of the column (i.e. the header), the row, and other structures in more complex tables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The first column often presents information dimension description by which the rest of the table is navigated.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tables may contain three or multiple dimensions and can be classified by the number of dimensions.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Multi-dimensional tables may have super-rows - rows that describe additional dimensions for the rows that are presented below that row and are usually grouped in a tree-like structure.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] This structure is typically visually presented with an appropriate number of white spaces in front of each stub's label.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] In literature tables often present numerical values, cumulative statistics, categorical values, and at times parallel descriptions in form of text.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] They can condense large amount of information to a limited space and therefore they are popular in scientific literature in many fields of study.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] As a communication tool, a table allows a form of generalization of information from an unlimited number of different social or scientific contexts.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] It provides a familiar way to convey information that might otherwise not be obvious or readily understood.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] For example, in the following diagram, two alternate representations of the same information are presented side by side.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] On the left is the NFPA 704 standard "fire diamond" with example values indicated and on the right is a simple table displaying the same values, along with additional information.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Both representations convey essentially the same information, but the tabular representation is arguably more comprehensible to someone who is not familiar with the NFPA 704 standard.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The tabular representation may not, however, be ideal for every circumstance (for example because of space limitations, or safety reasons).
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Modern software applications give users the ability to generate, format, and edit tables and tabular data for a wide variety of uses, such as in: word processing and spreadsheet applications, presentation software, and in HTML or another markup language.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Table cells are a key component in HTML and webpage building.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A programmer may specify dimensions for a table cell, and use them to hold sections of webpages.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A table cell in HTML is a non-empty element and is supposed to always be closed.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] There are two different kinds of table cell in HTML, namely: normal table cell and header cell.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] **<td>** denotes a table cell, the name implying 'data', while **<th>** denotes a table 'header'.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The two can be used interchangeably, but it is recommended that header cell be only used for the top and side headers of a table.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Furthermore, a table cell must be nested within a **<table>** tag *and* a **<tr>** (table row) tag.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] If there are more table cell tags in any given row than in any other, the particular **<tr>** must be given a colspan attribute declaring how many columns of cells wide it should be.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] By using the **rowspan** and **colspan** attributes, developers can combine multiple rows or columns, allowing them to design more complex and visually structured tables.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tables have uses in software development for both high-level specification and low-level implementation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Usage in software specification can encompass ad hoc inclusion of simple decision tables in textual documents through to the use of tabular specification methodologies, examples of which include Software Cost Reduction and Statestep.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Database systems often store data in structures called tables; in which columns are data fields and rows represent data records.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] There are several specific situations in which tables are routinely used as a matter of custom or formal convention.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] A table of contents (or simply contents, abbreviated as TOC), is a list usually part of the front matter preceding the main text of a book or other written work containing the titles of the text's sections, sometimes with descriptions.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Angles less than 45° are found on the left page, angles greater than 45° on the right.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Cosine, cotangent and cosecant are found by using the entry on the opposite page.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Mathematical tables are tables of information, usually numbers, showing the results of a calculation with varying arguments.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Trigonometric tables were used in ancient Greece and India for applications to astronomy and celestial navigation, and continued to be widely used until electronic calculators became cheap and plentiful in the 1970s, in order to simplify and drastically speed up computation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tables of logarithms and trigonometric functions were common in math and science textbooks, and specialized tables were published for numerous applications.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] In natural sciences, uses of tables include the periodic table in chemistry, and tide tables in oceanography.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The periodic table, also known as the periodic table of the elements, is an ordered arrangement of the chemical elements into rows ("periods") and columns ("groups").
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] An icon of chemistry, the periodic table is widely used in physics and other sciences.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] It is a depiction of the periodic law, which states that when the elements are arranged in order of their atomic numbers an approximate recurrence of their properties is evident.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] The table is divided into four roughly rectangular areas called blocks.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Elements in the same group tend to show similar chemical characteristics.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tide tables, sometimes called tide charts, are used for tidal prediction and show the daily times and levels of high and low tides, usually for a particular location.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tide heights at intermediate times (between high and low water) can be approximated by using the rule of twelfths or more accurately calculated by using a published tidal curve for the location.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Tide levels are typically given relative to a low-water vertical datum, e.g. the mean lower low water (MLLW) datum in the US.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] In medieval counting houses, the tables were covered with a piece of checkered cloth, to count money.*Exchequer* is an archaic term for the English institution which accounted for money owed to the monarch.
[src:pandas-dataframe/table-information] Thus the checkerboard tables of stacks of coins are a concrete realization of this information.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] This is a short introduction to pandas, geared mainly for new users.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] You can see more complex recipes in the Cookbook.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] `DataFrame`: a two-dimensional data structure that holds data like a two-dimension array or a table with rows and columns.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See the Intro to data structures section.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Creating a `Series` by passing a list of values, letting pandas create a default `RangeIndex`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Creating a `DataFrame` by passing a dictionary of objects where the keys are the column labels and the values are the column values.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] If you’re using IPython, tab completion for column names (as well as public attributes) is automatically enabled.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] As you can see, the columns `A`, `B`, `C`, and `D` are automatically tab completed.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] `E` and `F` are there as well; the rest of the attributes have been truncated for brevity.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See the Essential basic functionality section.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] While standard Python / NumPy expressions for selecting and setting are intuitive and come in handy for interactive work, for production code, we recommend the optimized pandas data access methods, `DataFrame.at()`, `DataFrame.iat()`, `DataFrame.loc()` and `DataFrame.iloc()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See the indexing documentation Indexing and Selecting Data and MultiIndex / Advanced Indexing.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See more in Selection by Label using `DataFrame.loc()` or `DataFrame.at()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See more in Selection by Position using `DataFrame.iloc()` or `DataFrame.iat()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Select rows where `df.A` is greater than `0`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] For NumPy data types, `np.nan` represents missing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] It is by default not included in computations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Reindexing allows you to change/add/delete the index on a specified axis.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Operations in general *exclude* missing data.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Operating with another `Series` or `DataFrame` with a different index or column will align the result with the union of the index or column labels.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] In addition, pandas automatically broadcasts along the specified dimension and will fill unaligned labels with `np.nan`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] `DataFrame.agg()` and `DataFrame.transform()` applies a user defined function that reduces or broadcasts its result respectively.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See more at Histogramming and Discretization.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] `Series` is equipped with a set of string processing methods in the `str` attribute that make it easy to operate on each element of the array, as in the code snippet below.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] pandas provides various facilities for easily combining together `Series` and `DataFrame` objects with various kinds of set logic for the indexes and relational algebra functionality in the case of join / merge-type operations.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Adding a column to a `DataFrame` is relatively fast.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] However, adding a row requires a copy, and may be expensive.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] We recommend passing a pre-built list of records to the `DataFrame` constructor instead of building a `DataFrame` by iteratively appending records to it.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] `merge()` enables SQL style join types along specific columns.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Grouping by multiple columns label forms `MultiIndex`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See the sections on Hierarchical Indexing and Reshaping.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] pandas has simple, powerful, and efficient functionality for performing resampling operations during frequency conversion (e.g., converting secondly data into 5-minutely data).
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] This is extremely common in, but not limited to, financial applications.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] pandas can include categorical data in a `DataFrame`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] For full docs, see the categorical introduction and the API documentation.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] When using Jupyter, the plot will appear using `plot()`.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] Otherwise use matplotlib.pyplot.show to show it or matplotlib.pyplot.savefig to write it to a file.
[src:pandas-dataframe/user-guide-10min] See Comparisons and Gotchas for an explanation and what to do.
